Date: Thu, 27 Aug 1998 11:30:22 -0500
From: CONNIE AUSTIN <CAUSTIN@idph.state.il.us>

An update on the leptospirosis outbreak.
The Springfield Dept. of Public Health, the Illinois Dept. of Public
Health, and the CDC are working to investigate the large lake outbreak of
leptospirosis. This lake is huge, 4,040 acres with a shoreline of 57 miles
and a storage capacity of 17 billion gallons; this is exceedingly unusual
in the history of leptospirosis outbreaks. The watershed is also large
providing many possibilities for animal reservoirs. We are exploring a
number of possibilities including wildlife, livestock and other domestic
and exotic animal testing.
At this point no source is being singled out. There is an extensive
wildlife preserve area, which is basically woods ideal for wild animal
habitat, esp around the area of greatest concern in the lake. We are
awaiting convalescent titers in the humans to more clearly establish the
serovars that are involved in the outbreak which might help in focusing on
a particular animal reservoir. Both triathletes from a June 21 event and
community cases have been confirmed with leptospirosis. We have not yet had
a positive culture from a human isolate which would be necessary to match
up using subtyping with any animal or water isolates which might occur.
It may be that we will not establish the source of this outbreak despite
our efforts. There was a heavy rainfall before the day of the triathlon
which may have led to ideal environmental conditions for this outbreak to
occur. This lake has not previously had any known leptospirosis cases
associated with it. Triathlons have been held for 10-15 years with no
problems.
This is a unique outbreak and we will hopefully learn much more about this
rare disease through the cooperation of the triathletes involved and the
work of many investigators.
--
Connie Austin, IDPH
e-mail: CAUSTIN@idph.state.il.us
